We serve Charlottesville VA, Warrenton, Culpeper and surrounding areas oServiceMaster of Charlottesville, Culpeper and Warrenton has served the Virginia Piedmont since 1992. Our managers, estimators, and technicians have decades of accumulated experience in the industry, with an unparalleled commitment to responsiveness, teamwork, and customer satisfaction.f Central Virginia. ServiceMaster of Charlottesville, Culpeper, and Warrenton are locally owned and operated franchises of ServiceMaster Restore®. As such, our owner, managers, and employees are part of the communities in which they serve, and are not represented by corporate decision-makers outside of the area. We invest locally, buy locally, and support the community through charitable works and donations. Proper training is critical component of any successful disaster restoration company. Our company, managers, estimators and technicians are certified by the Institute of Inspection, Cleaning and Restoration Certification (IICRC), a non-profit, independent certification body to set and promote high standards and ethics and to advance communication and technical proficiency within the inspection, cleaning and restoration service industries. Our IICRC certifications include: Water Remediation Technician, Applied Structural Drying, Applied Microbial Remediation, Fire and Smoke Damage Remediation, Carpet Repair and Reinstallation, Carpet Cleaning, and Odor Control. Additionally, ServiceMaster of Charlottesville, Culpeper, and Warrenton personnel hold certifications related to safety training, lead-safe practices, and duct cleaning. These certifications, combined with the long-term experience of our employees and the most stringent training/continuing education requirements in the industry, ensure our customers can trust their disaster restoration needs will be carefully and successfully addressed.

Full Description: Communication Software, Inc. (CSI) provides innovative technology solutions for market research, communication services and clean energy. **CSI** was founded by [Ashoke Bose](http://www.crunchbase.com/person/Ashoke-Bose) in 1991. The purpose of creating CSI was to market an innovative product **Strategic Network System** which is capable of simulating flow of information in a group of persons.  This product was tested by a Wall street brokerage firm to evaluate the value of "Word of Mouth" marketing strategy. This was much before the days of myspace or facebook. The result was interesting and was presented at the SUGI 18 (SAS User Group International) conference in New York in 1993. The market was not ready for such technology at that time. In 1992, _CSI_ conducted Fair Market Rent (FMR) studies for the City of Tucson Housing Authority. The officials of Tucson did not accept the Tucson FMR data provided by Housing and Urban Development (HUD), which was responsible for administering Section-8 Housing Assistance program in USA. City of Tucson contracted with CSI Consulting service to collect renters data in accordance with the HUD FMR Guidelines for List Assisted Random Digit Dialing (RDD) methodology. CSI's report proved that HUD's FMR was inaccurate for Tucson MSA. Therefore, City was given additional funding to meet the rental needs. By end of 1994, CSI became the market leader in providing FMR studies in USA. CSI conducted 10,000+ calls for each project by utilizing Computer Assisted Telephone Interview (CATI) system.  In addition to FMR projects, CSI conducted Seat Belt Use studies for Arizona, New Mexico, North Dakota and Maine. In 1995, CSI initiated OpinionUSA.com project for online data collection via internet.

Critics review the city's arts, entertainment, literary and restaurant scene. Listings of concerts, art exhibits, dance performances and other events are carried in the paper and in a comprehensive online events calendar. A popular weekly feature, the I LoveYou/IHate You column, is a distinctive collection of reader-submitted musings and rants on the frustrations and small victories of city life. The publication was established in November 1981 as a spinoff of the now defunct WXPN Express newsletter. Philadelphia City Paper distributes 70,000 copies in more than 2,000 locations throughout Philadelphia, its Pennsylvania suburbs and South Jersey. It is the most-read weekly in Pennsylvania. Its signature orange-colored boxes and wire racks can be found in more than 2,000 high-traffic areas in Center City Philadelphia, in cafes, small businesses and on many university campuses. Each year, City Paper publishes City Guide, a handy resource for new residents and college students, providing information about music venues, restaurants, shopping, transportation and the city's history. Description: Muscle mass diagnostics as a subscription service
Headquarters Regions: San Francisco Bay Area, West Coast, Western US
Full Description: As humans, our muscle mass is a primary indicator of our longevity, both as we develop early in life, as well as seek to maintain muscle mass throughout our adult and senior years. Current diagnostics only measure a more generalized lean mass or body fat, neither of which true indicators of strength and health, especially in the body compositions of young children. Yet, there does not exist an accurate way to measure direct skeletal muscle mass in any capacity. Flexaya is the first-to-market in offering a commercially available diagnostic to directly measure muscle mass. Using unique features of muscle tissue and creatine biology, Flexaya provides a simple, affordable approach to measure muscle mass, one that can be repeated at home through a subscription-based service model, all without the need for access to specialized equipment. We have validated this measure against the gold standard (MRI) with greater than 98% accuracy rate in both adults and children (see Clark J Appl Physiol 1985). At our respective academic institutions, we have implemented in this measure in a large, $1.5m NIH-funded study of more than 1400 older men, as well as in a large study of more than 100 infants and children with support from the Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation. The extensions of Flexaya’s testing method are vast, as studies underway indicate that muscle mass is perhaps the most sensitive metric to track growth stunting due to malnutrition, a global epidemic affecting nearly one-in-four children worldwide. As skeletal muscle is the largest organ in the body for glucose disposal, our measure may also have applications in diabetic research.  Flexaya’s method may well evolve as the standard diagnostic in what is an increasing appetite for self-diagnostic health and fitness data by the mass-market adult consumer, as well as become the defacto test for pediatricians and neonatologists to determine the trajectory of growth of infants and children.
Industry Groups: Biotechnology, Health Care, Science and Engineering, Sports
